Drunk with corruption
My friend Boris was about to leave my place, drunk.
I therefore suggested he not drive.
He asked me why.
"You've had a drink," I said to him, "haven't you got afraid of the police?"
Boris replied to me: "No, I have a document with the image of Benjamin Franklin, that always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped next to it.
Obviously, I knew that the police took bribes, but I worried that Boris might run into a corruptible policeman.
"It's impossible," Boris declared, "to join the traffic police department without buying your boss's silence."
"If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your boss's silence?"
Half of the drivers in Moscow use driver's licenses bought illegally.
"Those who try to do things by the book drown in bureaucratic red tape."
"For $100, you can drive in the city without any brakes!"
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, both before and after Lenin's October Revolution.
But never to the record-breaking levels seen today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
According to Boris, the only ones who don't accept bribes are those to whom none are offered.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a disaster or abandonment.
Everyone, from the police to the prosecutors, customs officials, and even the Kremlin: nowhere is anyone immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of Moscow's most beautiful suburbs.
It was a luxurious place but similar to a gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Examining the pretentious and tastelessly decorated houses, I asked who owned them and was told that one belonged to a deputy mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and yet another to the son of the Moscow prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax official.
Corruption now poses a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted so long if it were not led by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police officers who sell arms and supplies to the rebels.
Russian television recently showed a bus making a shuttle from Grozny to Moscow, the same bus that brought to Moscow the 120 kilograms of explosives used in the Dubrovka theater siege, where so many victims perished during the assault aimed at freeing the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A precaution well useless.
Nobody controls the buses anymore.
The driver, who had no idea what he was carrying, said he was stopped 50 times along his route and each time it was for the same thing.
A police officer came up to him and asked: "Do you know the price?" and the driver replied: "Of course, I do," paying the bribe before leaving.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, for days on the entire route.
The Chechen war continues indefinitely not only because the Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaïda and all "the international terrorist" community, but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, and civilians who accept bribes, as well as thieves who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal from them, sell arms and explosives to terrorists, maps showing minefields, and provide rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk blasts, the terrorists used arms bought from Russian army officers.
The Chechen rebels have modern arms.
Where do they come from ?
In the mountains where the Chechen rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels have their own stockpiles of ammunition, from which the arms are stolen and sold.
And not just arms: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no battle has been waged against this plague.
Punishing corruption more harshly?
This would only increase the prices of corruption.
The more severe the punishment, the more you'll have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they are themselves corrupt.
Thus, those referred to as "the common folk" view this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor, "Yes, of course, he steals, but look at all he's done for the city!"
The common folk don't like honest workers either.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 roubles, but by paying a small bribe, you can travel for 50 roubles.
The traveler and the inspector both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The inspector had stopped her, saying that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train.
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son to be called up for military service, buy an army clerk to erase his name from the list or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any university for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed recklessly, run red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, had understood the impossibility of winning the fight against corruption.
When the tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied to him: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
Over the centuries that have passed, the situation has deteriorated.
Erasing corruption might leave the state without citizens, but if we don't stop the spread of corruption, citizens will soon be left without a state.
